The press briefing by Press Secretary Jay Carney on January 10, 2012 covered several topics. Carney expressed condolences for the death of Tony Blankley, a former Reagan administration official. He also discussed the North American International Auto Show in Detroit, highlighting the success of the American automobile industry and the growth in manufacturing. Carney addressed questions about the resignation of Bill Daley as White House Chief of Staff and the appointment of Jack Lew as his successor. He also discussed the President's upcoming meeting with King Abdullah of Jordan, efforts to increase pressure on Iran and Syria, and the President's visit to the EPA. The briefing concluded with questions about the President's views on same-sex marriage and statements made by Mitt Romney and Sarah Palin.